	abstract = {Coalescing massive black hole binaries (MBHBs) of \$10{\textasciicircum}\{4-7\} {\textbackslash}rm M\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\$, forming in the aftermath of galaxy mergers, are primary targets of the space mission LISA, the \{{\textbackslash}it Laser Interferometer Space Antenna\}. An assessment of LISA detection prospects requires an estimate of the abundance and properties of MBHBs that form and evolve during the assembly of cosmic structures. To this aim, we employ a semi-analytic model to follow the co-evolution of MBHBs within their host galaxies. We identify three major evolutionary channels driving the binaries to coalescence: two standard paths along which the binary evolution is driven by interactions with the stellar and/or gaseous environment, and a novel channel where MBHB coalescence occurs during the interaction with a third black hole. For each channel, we follow the orbital evolution of MBHBs with physically motivated models that include a self-consistent treatment of the orbital eccentricity. We find that LISA will detect between \${\textbackslash}approx 25\$ and \${\textbackslash}approx 75\$ events per year depending on the seed model. We show that triple-induced coalescences can range from a few detected events up to \${\textbackslash}sim 30{\textbackslash}\%\$ of the total detected mergers. Moreover, even if the standard gas/stars-driven evolutionary channels should fail and MBHBs were to stall, triple interactions would still occur as a result of the hierarchical nature of galaxy formation, resulting in about \${\textbackslash}approx 10\$ to \${\textbackslash}approx 20\$ LISA detections per year. Remarkably, triple interactions among the black holes can produce coalescing binaries with large eccentricities (\${\textbackslash}gtrsim 0.9\$) upon entrance into the LISA band. This eccentricity will remain significant (\${\textbackslash}sim 0.1\$) also at merger, requiring suitable templates for parameter estimation.},
